<DOC><DOCNO> AP881205-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0321EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Venezuela-Glance     12-05 0317</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Venezuela-Glance,0325</SECOND><HEAD>Venezuela At-A-Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Venezuela-Election, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here are some facts and figures on Venezuela, where voters wentto the polls Sunday to elect their seventh president since anauthoritarian ruler, Gen. Marcos Perez Jimenez, was toppled in 1958:</TEXT><TEXT>   THE LAND _ Venezuela covers 352,143 square miles, an area largerthan Texas and Utah combined. It lies on the north coast of SouthAmerica, on the Caribbean and the Atlantic Ocean. It shares borderswith Brazil on the south, Colombia on the west and Guyana on theeast. It has unsettled border disputes with Guyana and Colombia.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE PEOPLE _ Venezuela has 18.43 million people, and itspopulation is growing at a rate of 2.9 percent, one of the highestrates in Latin America. The literacy rate is 90 percent, one of theregion's highest. More than 9.1 million people over 18, the votingage, are registered to vote by the Electoral Council, whichsupervises elections.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE ECONOMY _ Oil accounts for more than 90 percent of thenation's export revenue. Oil income this year will be $7.1 billion,down from $9.1 billion in 1987. The plunge in oil prices since theearly 1980s, coupled with a foreign debt of $33 billion, thwartedplans to expand and modernize the economy. The oil crunch is alsoresponsible for a sharp decline in the nation's per capita income _$2,782 in 1986, down from $3,408 in 1980.</TEXT><TEXT>   HISTORY _ Christopher Columbus discovered Venezuela _ named forLittle Venice _ in 1498. Venezuela declared independence in 1811 andSpain recognized the nation in 1821. Since its separation in 1830from a federation made up of Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela, thecountry has had 34 presidents, mostly a succesion of ``caudillos,''strongmen backed up by local militias, until 1959, when RomuloBetancourt became the first president of the modern era of democracy.</TEXT></DOC>